#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "Publishing DwC-A using the IPT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:111
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Assumption: Your data are already stored as a CSV/tab text file, or in one of the supported relational database management systems (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle, Sybase). Ideally, you are already using Darwin Core terms as column names, although this is not required.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:113
msgid "The xref:index.adoc[Integrated Publishing Toolkit (IPT)] is GBIF’s flagship tool for publishing DwC-As."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:115
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/index.adoc:38
msgid "The simplest way to begin using the IPT is to request a free account on a xref:data-hosting-centres.adoc[trusted data hosting centre] allowing you to manage your own datasets and publish them through GBIF.org without the hassle of setting up and maintaining the IPT on your own server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:117
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/index.adoc:40
msgid "Otherwise if want to setup your own instance of the IPT the xref:getting-started.adoc[Getting Started Guide] is your entry point."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:119
msgid "The IPT can be used to publish resource metadata, occurrence data, checklist data, and sampling-event data. The guide xref:how-to-publish.adoc[How to publish biodiversity data through GBIF.org] provides a simple set of instructions how to do so."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:121
msgid "The IPT outputs a DwC-A during publishing and supports automatic registration in the GBIF network. See the xref:manage-resources.adoc#visibility[IPT User Manual] for further details."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "Publishing DwC-A using GBIF Spreadsheet Templates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Assumption: The occurrence data, simple taxonomic data, or sampling-event data to be published are not yet captured in digital format OR a simple solution for creating a metadata document to describe a dataset is desired.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:127
msgid "GBIF provides a set of pre-configured Microsoft Excel spreadsheet files that serve as templates for capturing occurrence data, checklist data, and sampling-event data:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:129
msgid "xref:checklist-data.adoc#templates[Checklist data template]: suitable for basic species checklists"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:130
msgid "xref:occurrence-data.adoc#templates[Occurrence data template]: suitable for occurrence data (specimen, observation)"
msgstr ""

#. .  Resource metadata template: suitable for composing a metadata document - pending but imminent
#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:132
msgid "xref:sampling-event-data.adoc#templates[Sampling-event data template]: suitable for sampling-event data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:134
msgid "Each template provides inline help and instructions in the worksheets."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:136
msgid "To publish the data as a DwC-A, upload the templates to the IPT. Use the IPT's built-in metadata editor to enter dataset metadata. The guide xref:how-to-publish.adoc[How to publish biodiversity data through GBIF.org] provides a simple set of instructions how to do so. If you require an account on an IPT, it is highly recommended that you request an account on a xref:data-hosting-centres.adoc[trusted data hosting centre] located in your country."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "Publishing DwC-A manually"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:140
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Assumption: Data is already in a CSV/Tab text file, or in one of the supported relational database management systems (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle, Sybase). The publisher does not wish to host an IPT instance but does have access to a web server.*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:142
msgid "DwC-As can be created without installing any dedicated software. These instructions target data managers who are familiar with the dataset to be published and are comfortable working with their data management system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:144
msgid "Below is a set of instructions on how to manually create a DwC-Archive:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:146
msgid "Unless the data are already stored in a CSV/Tab text file, the publisher needs to prepare a text file(s) from the source. If the data are stored in a database, generate an output of delimited text from the source database into an outfile. Most database management systems support this process; an example is given in the Annex to this guide, below, in the section “Outputting Data From a MySQL Database Into a Textfile”. As the metafile maps the columns of the text file to Darwin Core terms, it is not necessary to use Darwin Core terms as column header in the resultant text file, though it may help to reduce errors. A general recommendation is to produce a single core data file and a single file for each extension if the intention is to output data tied to an extension."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:147
msgid "Create a Metafile: There are three different ways to generate the file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:148
msgid "Create it manually by using an XML editor and using a sample metafile as a guiding example. A complete description of the metafile format can be found in the http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/guides/text/index.htm[Darwin Core Text Guide]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:152
#, no-wrap
msgid "figures/dwc-a_assistant.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:155
msgid "Create it using the online application http://tools.gbif.org/dwca-assistant/[Darwin Core Archive Assistant] Simply select the fields of data to be published, provide some details about the files and save the resultant XML. This only needs to be done once unless the set of published fields changes at some later time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:157
msgid "this tool is no longer supported by GBIF. Support for the Event core is missing. Publishers also need to manually add term dwc:taxonID to Taxon core and dwc:occurrenceID to Occurrence core, to ensure they are explicitly included."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:160
msgid "Create a metadata file (eml.xml) that describes the data resource. Complete instructions on doing this are available in the xref:gbif-metadata-profile.adoc[GBIF Extended Metadata Profile: How-To Guide]. It is best practice to include a metadata file and the simplest way to produce one is using the IPT's built-in metadata editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:161
msgid "Ensure the data files, the metafile (meta.xml) and metadata file (eml.xml) are in the same directory or folder. Compress the folder using one of the support compression formats. The result is a DwC-A."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:163
msgid "Metadata authored using IPT can be output as an RTF document, which can then be submitted as ‘Data Paper’ manuscript to Zookeys, PhytoKeys and BioRisks. See instructions to authors for ‘Data Paper’ submission to these journals."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:164
#, no-wrap
msgid "Validation of DwC-As"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:167
msgid "GBIF provides an online https://www.gbif.org/tools/data-validator[DwC-Archive Validator] that performs the following checks:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:169
msgid "The metafile (meta.xml) is valid XML and complies with the http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/guides/text/[Darwin Core Text Guidelines]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:170
msgid "The content complies with the known extensions and terms registered within the GBIF network. Note GBIF runs a production and a development registry that keeps track of extensions; the validator uses the production registry."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:171
msgid "The resource description file (eml.xml) is valid XML and complies with the GBIF Metadata Profile schema and the official EML schema."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:172
msgid "Referential integrity — that mapped ID terms in extension files reference existing core records."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:173
msgid "All core IDs are unique"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:174
msgid "That no verbatim null values are found in the data. For example NULL or \\N"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:175
msgid "Taxonomy and locations pass typical GBIF interpretation processes (e.g. coordinates are within the specified country)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/dwca-guide.adoc:177
msgid "To use the validator:"
msgstr ""

